Anonymous Fri 01 Jan 2021 19:27:48 No.35170775 Report
Quoted By:
>>35170630
Do you have any outlines done?
Doesn't take much, maybe just an incomplete sentence to summarize what's happened or a key emotion per scene.
The point is to leave yourself something that gets words down each session, and to have questions for yourself at the end of each session. What could go wrong? How do I/you/they solve things? Did I just introduce/advance a character conflict?

Breaking the larger task of a story into chunks, and breaking those up until you have manageable bits, is a good keystone to success.
Also helps keep you from wondering how to push onward.

I naturaly used a word count because I actually write in Word of all things, so I always measured my things. I tended to settle for about 1.2k words a day, but the issue with that is simply that life isn't stable enough for it and I haven't been able to write nearly as often, so it's degraded to the ocasional daily 600. The most important thing for those who can write is to write consistently with a set time to enforce a good habit, after that it's a matter of how much you planned, how much the story inspires you and how productive you are feeling.

20k words a month is more than respectable, but as cliche as it might sound, I'd take 10k quality words over 30 of purple prose. Don't stress about the count so much as how well it flows, sounds and how human and non human you can make people sound. Induce the Dream state on people, keep their immersion onto your writing, and you'll make something wonderful for sure.

Anonymous Sat 02 Jan 2021 12:24:22 No.35190620 Report
Quoted By:
>>35190519
I think you're pushing yourself too hard if you find that you can't write the day after a binge. I've mentioned this a lot of time, but I think consistency trumps quantity in every single situation. If you can write 300 words a day, every single day, you're going to get more done than if you write 1500 words once a week. On top of that, you're going to find it a lot more relaxing and natural when you sit down to write, since you're not regularly checking your word count to objectively measure your progress but instead focusing on the process of writing itself. Build a routine and establish positive habits, then work on improving yourself from that point and you can push your daily word count organically, instead of at the cost of your sanity
